annotation.TEXT: The writers thought this line was from an Ivory Liquid ad in the ‘70s, in which a teenage boy mistakes a mom’s hands for her teenage daughter’s; in fact, it’s from a Grape-Nuts ad.
Even for its time (1960), MST3K Episode 802, The Leech Woman, painted an out-of-touch, condescending portrait of African culture that was all huts and boar masks.

In a 1992 episode of The Simpsons, the girl next door reads Bart’s palm, prophesying, “Oh man, you’re gonna be rich! There’s the swimming pool!” and spits in his hand. The gag existed before the show.
“Say Yes” is a jingle for Martini & Rossi vermouth from the early ‘70s; it was performed by Burt Bacharach.
Ella Fitzgerald was generally considered to be one of the greatest scat singers in jazz, alongside Mel Tormé and Cab Calloway.
“If you lived here, you’d be home by now” is a common ad slogan for apartment complexes on banners and billboards, usually put up facing freeways.
“T-zone” is a buzzword in the world of cosmetics and skin care—it’s the T-shaped area across the forehead and down the bridge of the nose that is notoriously oily and difficult to deal with.
The phrase “liquid metal” was made famous by the 1991 film Terminator 2: Judgment Day. The killer android played by Robert Patrick spent most of the movie disguised as a motorcycle cop.
In 2015 Girl Scouts sold nearly 200 million boxes of cookies, which provide about 60 percent of the funding for local troops.
The longtime company mascot of Aunt Jemima, a racially condescending “mammy” caricature originating in 19th-century minstrel shows, was wisely given a makeover in the late ‘60s.
Cab forward trains and trucks have the driver’s compartment farther toward the front of the vehicle, offering better visibility or more passenger space.
Most famous for its “little black dress,” the Chanel fashion house also sells accessories, cosmetics, handbags, and fragrances (including the iconic Chanel No. 5).
This is the theme played on the Tonight Show when Johnny Carson would come onstage, entering through the heavy curtains that hung at the back of the stage.
The Mexican food company Ortega was founded in California around the turn of the century by Emilio Ortega.
In 1997, four months before this episode originally aired, actress Elizabeth Taylor had an operation to remove a benign brain tumor.
Nabisco lost its trademark for “Saltines” in the US in 1907 when it became a brand eponym for all similar crackers. It’s still TM in Australia, though.
Emmett Kelly’s persona of “Weary Willie,” the tramp clown, was famous around the world; he performed in Ringling Brothers Barnum & Bailey Circus for 14 seasons.
George C. Scott was an intense actor best known for playing General Buck Turgidson in Dr. Strangelove and the title role in Patton.
Quinn only composed for this film and a 1964 short called Goof on the Loose, also directed by Ray Dennis Steckler.
Town Without Pity is a 1961 film starring Kirk Douglas as a military lawyer assigned to defend four American soldiers charged with raping a young German girl.
Snap, Crackle, and Pop are the long-time advertising imps for Kellogg’s Rice Krispies cereal, designed by Vernon Grant in 1933.
On The Tracey Ullman Show, host Ullman would bring the evening to a close with vigorous gesturing and the parting words “Go home!”
In a diverting 1990 ad for Égoïste men’s fragrance, an entire building of incensed French women rushed to their balconies to yell “Égoïste!” at the unseen philanderer living in the middle apartment.
Wendy Carlos is an American trans woman composer; she is best known for pioneering the Moog synthesizer and writing the scores for A Clockwork Orange and The Shining.
A line from “Redemption Song,” an atypically somber acoustic song by Bob Marley & the Wailers.
The term “teamster,” now used to refer to a truck driver, was a nickname for 19th-century wagon handlers, who had to manage teams of draft animals during America’s westward expansion.
Craggy actor Ernest Borgnine is perhaps best known as Quinton McHale in the ‘60s TV series McHale’s Navy. He won an Oscar for his title role in the movie Marty.
While Welk appealed mainly to a whitebread, middle-aged, Midwestern audience, he was also the first variety-show host to hire a black performer as a regular: tap dancer Arthur Duncan.
Kid ‘n Play were a rap duo in the late ‘80s and starred in several House Party movies in the ‘90s. Christopher “Kid” Reid had a notoriously huge high-top fade hairstyle.
And let us know if we missed any references!
Actress Joan Collins is best known for playing Alexis Morrell Carrington Colby Dexter Rowan on the prime-time TV soap opera Dynasty in the ‘80s.
No-Pest Strips are used to kill a wide variety of insects. They are coated with DDVP, which can kill you if you eat it, inhale it, or even spill it on your skin. Proceed with caution.
Popular with teenagers, Boone’s Farm is a brand of bottom-shelf wine cooler/malt liquor made by the E. & J. Gallo Winery.
Slash-and-burn agriculture is a traditional method of land-clearing, accounting for much of the destruction of South America’s tropical rainforests.
The famous WWI recruitment poster by artist J.M. Flagg, which showed Uncle Sam pointing sternly at the viewer, was based on an earlier British poster showing then-War Secretary Lord Kitchener.
Elisabeth Shue was nominated for an Oscar for Leaving Las Vegas, with Nicolas Cage as her alcohol-soaked co-star.
The Fatburger fast food chain has been immortalized in song by a number of rappers, including Notorious B.I.G., Tupac Shakur, and Ice Cube.
George M. Cohan was a Broadway and vaudeville legend who wrote popular tunes like “Over There,” “Give My Regards to Broadway,” and “You’re a Grand Old Flag.”
A line from “Rosalita (Come Out Tonight),” a 1973 Bruce Springsteen song.
The Apollo Theater in NYC has showcased emerging African-American performers since 1934. Its Amateur Nights launched the careers of Ella Fitzgerald, James Brown, and Michael Jackson, among others.
Married in real life, Alfred Lunt and Lynn Fontanne were a Broadway acting couple from the ‘20s onwards, almost inseparable on stage and screen.
A reference to the 1982 film noir comedy Dead Men Don’t Wear Plaid, starring Steve Martin.
Did we miss any references? Let us know in the comments!
Dictaphone is a brand of dictation machine, first sold by the Columbia Graphophone Company in 1907.
Gladys Knight & the Pips was one of the most popular R&B groups of the ‘60s and ‘70s. The Pips were the backup singers on such songs as “Midnight Train to Georgia.”
The Clones of Dr. Funkenstein is a 1976 album by funk band Parliament.
Charles Whitman was a student at UT Austin in 1966 when he went to a tower on campus and opened fire, killing 14 and wounding 31 before police killed him 2 hours later.
On The Andy Griffith Show, Andy’s love interest was schoolteacher Helen Crump (played by Aneta Corsaut). In 1968 the two married and left the show, which then became Mayberry R.F.D.
Magnum is a brand of condom, manufactured by Trojan to be 20% larger than its regular condom. It was introduced in 1989.
One of the writers’ favorite phrases was “Hooker’s a good cop!”—a reference to the ‘80s cop show T.J. Hooker, starring William “Captain Kirk” Shatner.
A parody of a ‘70s-era slogan for Libby’s canned goods: “When it says Libby’s, Libby’s, Libby’s on the label, label, label you will like it, like it, like it on your table, table, table.”
The origin of the phrase “23 skidoo,” meaning “Scram!”, is unclear, but it dates back to at least the turn of the 20th century.
A line from the title song of the 1945 Rodgers & Hammerstein musical State Fair.
Local clothing manufacturer Abraham Zapruder’s shaky home movie of President Kennedy’s assassination in a motorcade in Dallas is the only film record we have of the crime.
Pee-wee’s Playhouse was a critically acclaimed children’s TV series starring comedian Paul Reubens as the child-adult Pee-wee Herman. It was cancelled after Reubens’ arrest for indecent exposure.
Count Orlok (Max Schreck) was the bat-like bloodsucker in the 1922 German Expressionist film Nosferatu, eine Symphonie des Grauens (“Nosferatu, a Symphony of Horror”), directed by F.W. Murnau.
In Bananas, Woody Allen tells his therapist a dream in which some monks are carrying him, crucified, into a parking space when they get into a fight with another monks-and-martyr squad.
After President Ronald Reagan was shot in 1981, his wife Nancy turned to an astrologer, Joan Quigley. She used Quigley’s advice to guide Reagan’s schedule, which caused a scandal in 1988.
Voiceover professional Elwood Edwards supplied the famous sound bite used by America Online to inform its users of new email.
Schick is a brand of safety razors and shaving products owned by Edgewell Personal Care.
Nana Mouskouri is an internationally renowned Greek classical and jazz singer. Famous for her thick glasses, she has recorded albums in multiple languages.
Dippity-Do hair gel was introduced in the ‘60s. It came in two colors—green for regular strength and pink for extra strength.
Phonograph cylinders were the first commercially available recording medium. Thomas Edison invented a tin foil cylinder in 1877 but later changed to wax.
“Silent Night” was translated into English in 1859 by an Episcopal priest.
Polonius is the garrulous counselor to the king who winds up getting punctured behind an arras in the William Shakespeare play Hamlet.
Schick razors were first sold in 1926.
Jerry Markbreit (not Arkbreit) was an NFL referee from 1977-1998. When you add his college football years, Markbreit was a football official for 43 seasons.
Renée Richards is an American trans woman pro tennis player who successfully sued in the ‘70s to be ruled eligible to play as a woman.
Shiatsu is a Japanese form of massage therapy, derived from an earlier form of Chinese bodywork called tui na, which arrived in Japan in the 8th century CE.
The horrific Manson Family murders of 1969 were apparently committed because Charles Manson was hoping to start a race war.
A line from the song “London Calling” by The Clash.
DC Comics villain Catwoman’s real name is (usually) Selina Kyle; she is most often depicted as carrying a whip while wearing skintight leather or vinyl suits and committing thefts.
The University of Wisconsin-Stout is a polytechnic university in Menomonie. Wisconsin universities seem prone to throwing post-winter bashes: Spring Flings, May Fetes, even Dormsylvania.
Rod Serling’s introduction to the TV series The Twilight Zone varied from season to season, but it always contained a reference to an uncanny dimension.
In Cold Blood is a “nonfiction novel” by Truman Capote about the murder of a Kansas farm family by two ex-convicts looking for money. The film version starred Robert Blake.

Aeschylus was an ancient Greek playwright, known for his Oresteia trilogy. Per legend, he was killed when an eagle, mistaking his bald head for a rock, dropped a turtle on him to crack open its shell.
Glen or Glenda is bad-movie director Ed Wood Jr.’s tribute to cross-dressing, transvestism, transsexualism, and angora. It starred Wood himself as the titular Glen/Glenda.
The Incredibly Strange Creatures Who Stopped Living and Became Mixed-Up Zombies.
Actor Ted Danson is best known for playing bar owner Sam Malone on Cheers as well as the title role on Becker.
Livingston Taylor is an American easy-listening singer-guitarist. He is the younger brother of musician James Taylor.
Eva Gabor, who starred as Lisa Douglas in Green Acres, was a Hungarian-American actress and socialite.
Former Senator Bob Dole ran as the Republican candidate for vice president in 1976 and for president in 1996. He was unsuccessful both times.
“I came here to drink myself to death” is what Ben Sanderson (Nicolas Cage) intends for himself in Leaving Las Vegas.
Ultraconservative North Carolina Senator Jesse Helms fought the Civil Rights Act and tried to make African-American Senator Carol Moseley Braun cry by singing “Dixie.” (He failed.)
Singer/actor Joel Grey is best known for playing the Master of Ceremonies in both the stage and film versions of Cabaret.
Dennis James was an announcer and game show host for decades on such shows as Name That Tune. He was also a frequent telethon host.
Steckler has a cameo in the Arch Hall Jr. film Eegah!, as the guy who gets pushed into the pool by Richard Kiel. He also directed and co-starred in Hall’s film Wild Guitar.
Visa began in 1958 as a Bank of America pilot program and took the name Visa in 1976. MasterCard was known as Master Charge when it was founded in 1966.
Grimley was a comic character created by Martin Short for SCTV and used later on Saturday Night Live: a thin, nerdy guy with a spike of lacquered hair standing straight up from his skull.
Edgar Winter is an albino blues/jazz/experimental musician whose best-known song is “Frankenstein,” which hit #1 in 1973.
Hammond organs are electric organs, originally invented to provide cheap, low-scale organs for churches, but quickly adopted by jazz musicians.
A paraphrase of the famous line from the 1971 film Dirty Harry, starring Clint Eastwood.
Thanks for watching this fully-annotated presentation of The Incredibly Strange Creatures Who Stopped Living and Became Mixed-Up Zombies.
In the 1964 Christmas special Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer, Hermey (not Herbie) the Misfit Elf dreams of being a dentist rather than a toymaker.
A reference to Bela Lugosi’s hypnotic character in MST3K Episode 423, Bride of the Monster, though the first use of this riff was in Episode 302, Gamera.
Big Head Todd and the Monsters is a Colorado-based soft-rock band, best known for the 1993 song “Bittersweet.”
Actress Elizabeth Taylor has launched several perfumes under her name, including Passion and White Diamonds, but Poison is made by Christian Dior.
An imitation of the chorus from the 1965 Smokey Robinson and the Miracles hit “Ooo Baby Baby”; Linda Ronstadt had a hit version in 1978.
The sound effect for the phaser energy weapons used on Star Trek was created by playing an electric guitar backwards and adding some harp sounds.
The concept of “healing your wounded inner child” was big in the early ‘90s, popularized by psychologist John Bradshaw.
Noam Chomsky is a distinguished philosopher and linguist who holds a dissenting opinion on almost every facet of modern capitalism and American policy.
Laverne & Shirley starred Penny Marshall and Cindy Williams as roommates who worked together in a Milwaukee brewery.
Jaco Pastorius was an innovative bass guitarist who suffered from bipolar disorder complicated by alcohol and drug abuse. He died in 1987 after a fight with a club bouncer.
Rice-A-Roni was originally based on a recipe for rice pilaf, taught to the company’s founders by a survivor of the Armenian genocide who lived with them in San Francisco.
And here’s a rendition of “Chest Fever” for your enjoyment.
A reference to the villainous mesmerist from MST3K Episode 808, The She Creature, and his sad little auditorium.
A paraphrase of the slogan for Norelco razors: “The first blade lifts the hair and the second blade cuts.”
Most of the “official” James Bond films open with the so-called “gunbarrel sequence,” accompanied by the famous theme written by Monty Norman.
After Fidel Castro seized power in Cuba in 1958, the US banned travel to the island. A wave of airplane hijackings followed: of 111 hijacking attempts from 1968-72, 90 were to Cuba.
Hank and Larry are the names of a feuding gay couple in the 1968 Broadway play (and 1970 movie) The Boys in the Band.
Führer is a German word meaning “leader”; it was appropriated by Hitler as one of his personal titles and used as a substitute for the office of president when it was dissolved.
Incredibly Strange Etc. was filmed at The Pike, a seaside amusement complex in Long Beach, CA, that featured cabarets, theaters, and dance halls to amuse locals and visiting sailors.
Grimley got his own animated series in 1988: The Completely Mental Misadventures of Ed Grimley. It lasted 13 episodes.
The cartoon “Goofus and Gallant,” meant to teach children social lessons, has been featured in Highlights magazine since 1948.
The U.S. territory of Guam is on the other side of the International Date Line, one day ahead of the rest of the country—hence its slogan, “Guam: where America’s day begins.”
Holly Golightly (played by Audrey Hepburn) is the devil-may-care heroine of the film Breakfast at Tiffany’s. One of her outfits famously included an enormous mushroom-cap-shaped hat.
David Schwimmer is a gangly actor best known for playing Ross Geller on the sitcom Friends.
“Drummer Boy” was written by Katherine Kennicott Davis, an American music teacher and composer, in 1941.
Totes are a brand of rubber overshoes. The company started making them in Cincinnati in 1924, along with umbrellas, gloves, and other rain gear.
A Beck’s beer ad from 1996 showed ships sailing and suns setting and people enjoying good, wholesome beer, all to the strains of “Sail Away” by German rocker Hans Hartz.
In the ‘50s urban legend “Spiders in the Beehive,” a girl with a huge bouffant hairdo discovers it has become home to thousands of spider eggs.
The Autobiography of Miss Jane Pittman is a 1971 novel by Ernest J. Gaines, about a 100-year-old African-American woman in the Deep South. In 1974 it was adapted as a TV movie.
Dean Martin and Jerry Lewis were a phenomenally successful comedy team during the ‘50s, starring in a string of movies that included Sailor Beware and Living It Up.
In the “fictionalized” version of Pee-wee’s adventures in Pee-wee’s Big Adventure, James Brolin stars as “P.W. Herman.”
An imitation of John Banner (co-star of MST3K Episode 417, Crash of the Moons) as inept German Sergeant Hans Schultz in Hogan’s Heroes.
Although Edison was a pioneer in early recorded music, he himself could not enjoy the results: he was largely deaf, possibly due to a bout of scarlet fever in childhood.
“Take Me Out to the Ball Game” is a Tin Pan Alley baseball tune written in 1908 by Jack Norworth and Albert Von Tilzer.
“Dead man walking” was once used to identify a death-row prisoner. The phrase was used as the title of a book by Sister Helen Prejean, an anti-death penalty activist.
Sabrina, the Teenage Witch was a TV sitcom, based on a comic book, about a teenage witch, her witch aunts, and a talking cat puppet named Salem. There was also an earlier animated series.
Bob Dylan is the folk singer’s folk singer, a counterculture icon who got his start in the cultural revolution of the ‘60s.
Fancy Feast cat food, introduced in 1982, was one of the first “gourmet” cat foods; ads showed it served in a crystal goblet to a snooty white Persian.
An imitation of comedian Jerry Lewis, from the popular team of Martin and Lewis.
Garth Hudson, keyboardist for The Band, is also a respected session musician, playing with John Hammond Jr., Neko Case, and Bob Dylan.
Bing Crosby’s version of “Silent Night” is the third best-selling single of all time.
Other films Steckler acted in (usually under a stage name): Wild Ones on Wheels, The Thrill Killers, and Body Fever. He also directed the latter two.
The Indigo Girls are a folk rock duo, one of the staples of the Lilith Fair in the ‘90s.
Rome (in Italian, Roma) is more than 2,500 years old, with a current population of nearly 2.7 million.
Madeleine Albright held the position of U.S. Secretary of State from 1997-2001; prior to that, she was US Ambassador to the UN from 1993-97.
Benazir Bhutto was the first woman elected to lead a Muslim nation. She was prime minister of Pakistan twice, and was assassinated while running for a third time.
Singer Lesley Gore was best known for her ‘60s pop hits “It’s My Party” and “Sunshine, Lollipops and Rainbows.”
Gower Champion was a Tony Award–winning choreographer of Broadway successes like Bye Bye Birdie and Hello, Dolly! Earlier in his career, he worked on glossy film musicals like Show Boat.
An imitation of Robert Young from the ‘50s TV sitcom Father Knows Best. He called his youngest daughter Kathy “Kitten.”
Brian Boitano is an American champion figure skater. In 1988 he won both the gold medal at the Olympics and the world figure skating championship, turning pro shortly thereafter.
South Beloit, IL, is a small city close to Rockford, near the Wisconsin border. It was originally named Turtle after a local Native American tribe.
Red Buttons was an old-style vaudeville comedian. In the mid-‘60s he played a Max Smart-type secret agent named Henry Phyfe on a TV sitcom, clad in a suit and tie and a fedora.
Bryant Gumbel is a journalist who co-hosted The Today Show for 15 years. His older brother, Greg, is an NFL sportscaster for CBS. They have two sisters, Rhonda and Renne.
JoAnne Akalaitis is a stage director, writer, and actor known for extravagant modernist productions of the classics.
Brought to you by the Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Super-sizing was a technique pioneered by McDonald’s in the ‘90s to get customers to buy more food. It was phased out in 2004, as public disapproval rose along with America’s soaring obesity rates.
“Silent Night” (“Stille Nacht, heilige Nacht”) is a popular Christmas carol, with lyrics and music by an Austrian priest and an Austrian schoolteacher, respectively, in 1818.
An ad jingle for Gillette disposable razors, composed by songwriter Jake Holmes.
“Sieg heil” (“Hail victory”) was one of the compulsory greetings of Nazi Germany, usually performed at a rally or in conjunction with the Nazi salute.
Paul Reubens co-wrote and starred in another film, 2016’s Pee-wee’s Big Holiday, when he was 63.
The Emir is Kuwait’s head of state, a position that has been held by a member of the House of Al-Sabah since 1752.
Michael Flatley’s Riverdance was first performed at the 1994 Eurovision Song Contest in Dublin.
Steckler’s later adult films included French Throat, Sex Rink, and the magnificently titled Lust Vegas Joyride.
Lady Remington is an electric razor introduced in the ‘60s.
Fully annotated by The Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Elvis Presley appeared on The Ed Sullivan Show three times. For his last performance, shocked by his energy and sexually suggestive moves, the network shot him only from the waist up.
Steve Prefontaine was a middle-long distance runner who won nearly every race he competed in. He died in a car accident at the age of 24.
Albert Speer was a German architect and Nazi who churned out the imperialistic spectacles that Hitler envisioned for the Third Reich.
The Godfather of Soul, James Brown, was also known as the Hardest-Working Man in Show Business.
Probably a mashup of actress Rue McClanahan, best known as man-hungry southern belle Blanche Devereaux on The Golden Girls, and famed hockey player Wayne Gretzky.
Author Julie Nixon Eisenhower is the youngest daughter of 37th President Richard Nixon and wife of David Eisenhower, grandson of 34th President Dwight Eisenhower.
The most famous Dr. Seuss hat is, of course, the red-and-white-striped top hat sported by the Cat in the Hat.
The mythical selkie is a seal that sheds its skin to take on human form on land. There was a resurgence of interest in selkie mythology after the 1994 film The Secret of Roan Inish.
A reference to the glorious movie theme in MST3K Episode 619, Red Zone Cuba, as sung by John Carradine in the throes of a death rattle.
Allen Ginsberg was a poet and the founding father of the Beat movement, whose angst he expressed in works like “Howl.”
The Crips (who wear blue) and the Bloods (who wear red) are two major LA-based African-American street gangs known for decades of warfare, beginning in the ‘70s.
The Republic of Chad is a country in central Africa that saw a lengthy civil war beginning in 1965, followed by squabbling among the victors, followed by a refugee crisis from neighboring Sudan.
Other terms for the practice of eating a meal and fleeing a restaurant without paying the tab: dine and ditch, chew and screw, eat it and beat it, doing a runner, and beating the check.
Andrei Gromyko was made Soviet ambassador to the newly formed UN in 1946, where he wielded his veto power with such frequency and vigor that he became known as “Mr. Nyet.”
Jaye P. Morgan was a popular singer during the ‘50s, but her true claim to fame came as a panelist on The Gong Show in the ‘70s.
Sam Harris is an openly gay American singer whose first big break was as a competitor on Star Search in 1984, singing “Over the Rainbow.”
Tom Petty is the musician/songwriter behind Tom Petty and the Heartbreakers; he has also played with the Traveling Wilburys and Mudcrutch.
“Chest Fever” is an instrument-heavy 1968 song by The Band that begins with a “Toccata and Fugue”-esque organ solo.
Australopithecus africanus is an early ancestor of modern humans that lived 2-3 million years ago in southern Africa.
Actor/singer Tab Hunter was a teen idol in the ‘50s who had a #1 hit with the song “Young Love.” Actress Yvonne De Carlo is best known today for playing Lily Munster in The Munsters.
A paraphrase of the opening line from the Jeannie C. Riley song “Harper Valley PTA.”
“Mother” Maybelle Carter played banjo, guitar, and autoharp for the Carter Family country-folk group from the ‘20s-‘40s and later toured with her daughters as Mother Maybelle and the Carter Sisters.
Marina Oswald is the Russian-born widow of Lee Harvey Oswald, assassin of President John F. Kennedy.
From the song “Wipe Out” by the Surfaris. The voice on the song belongs to the band’s manager, Dale Smallin.
Actor Nicolas Cage is known for many leading roles across a range of genres, although financial troubles in recent years have led to a multitude of terrible films.

Thomas the Tank Engine is the star of a series of children’s books by W.V. Audry, later turned into a TV show. The theme song doesn’t seem to have a title, but it does include choo-choo sound effects.
Michael Flatley choreographed the original production of the immensely popular Riverdance, but after disputes over creative control, he quit and cobbled together his own show, Lord of the Dance.
The Odd Couple is a Neil Simon play/movie/TV show about two poker buddies, one messy and one neat, whose friendship is tested when they move in together.
A popular catchphrase of The Three Stooges, a slapstick comedy trio that appeared in more than 200 shorts from the ‘30s into the ‘50s.
A line from “King Tut,” a 1978 comic song written and performed by comedian Steve Martin, backed by members of the Nitty Gritty Dirt Band (calling themselves the Toot Uncommons).
A reference to King Kong’s disastrous debut performance in the classic film King Kong. The wording itself is probably taken from George Orwell’s 1936 essay “Shooting an Elephant.”
Singer Eydie Gormé’s biggest hit was 1963’s “Blame It on the Bossa Nova.”
The Blue Angels are the official flight demonstration squadron of the US Navy. Since 1946, the Angels have lost 26 pilots in training accidents or aerial displays.
The Six Flags amusement park chain is named after the six national flags that have flown over Texas over the years: Spain, France, Mexico, the Republic of Texas, the Confederacy, and the US.
Sprite was originally marketed in Germany under the name Fanta Klare Zitrone.
Comedian Jackie Mason has had a string of successful one-man shows on Broadway. He has also appeared in TV shows and movies, including The Ed Sullivan Show and The Jerk.
Ethel Kennedy, the widow of the assassinated Robert F. Kennedy, contributed 11 children to the Kennedy clan.
Gloria Steinem was one of the leaders of the feminist movement in the ‘70s.
Flavorite is a line of grocery products manufactured by Eden Prairie, Minnesota-based SuperValu Inc.
Yoo-hoo is a chocolate-flavored drink, invented in the ‘20s as a substitute for chocolate milk that wouldn’t go bad in hot weather.
Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, popularly known as Jackie O, was the wife of President John F. Kennedy. After his assassination, she married Greek shipping magnate Aristotle Onassis.
Two different beaches in LA, one in Santa Monica and the other in Venice Beach, are called “Muscle Beach.” Both are named for the bodybuilding exhibitions and gyms located there.
Before Morrissey was the lead singer for popular post-punk band The Smiths, he fronted two unsuccessful bands: The Nosebleeds and Slaughter & the Dogs.
“Gobi” means “waterless place” in Mongolian, and thanks to human depredation, the Gobi Desert is one of the most rapidly expanding areas of desertification in the world.
An imitation of Lawrence Welk; dancers Cissy King and Bobby Burgess were regulars on the TV variety series The Lawrence Welk Show.
Nazis hated homosexuals as well as Jews; gays found within the party were murdered.
Abbie Hoffman was a far-left political activist and career protestor; he co-founded the Yippies, went on trial as one of the Chicago Seven, and wrote Steal This Book.
Hayward, of “giant fiberglass muskie” fame, is a tiny lake town in NW Wisconsin. Jim Mallon and Kevin J. Murphy worked on the movie Blood Hook, which was filmed there.
In 1991, Danny “Partridge Family” Bonaduce was arrested for assaulting a transvestite prostitute he had mistaken for a woman. He was sentenced to probation.
Estée Lauder launched the Clinique cosmetic line along with a dermatologist after reading an article written by the doctor in Vogue.
The name “Passaic” is derived from the Lenape word pahsayèk, possibly meaning “valley” or “peace.”
Prancer and Dancer are traditionally two of Santa’s reindeer, first mentioned in the 1823 poem “A Visit From St. Nicholas” by Clement Clarke Moore.
Grimley was famous for the catch phrase “Completely mental, I must say.”
Lines from the opening of “Help!”, released in 1965 by The Beatles.
Actress Glenn Close has starred in movies like Fatal Attraction, Dangerous Liaisons, and more. Also a riff on Hendrix’s band, the Jimi Hendrix Experience.
With annotations provided by The Annotated MST website.
The Citadel is the state military college of South Carolina. It admitted its first female day student in 1995, under court order. Currently about 8 percent of cadets are women.
Ross Perot, founder of data-processing giant EDS, ran twice as a third-party candidate for president in the ‘90s. He won 19 percent and 8 percent, respectively.
Heidi Fleiss, aka the Hollywood Madam, was arrested in 1993 for running a prostitution ring in LA. Her customers allegedly included many Hollywood celebrities.
Neil Young is an influential singer/songwriter who has played with Crosby, Stills, Nash & Young and Crazy Horse and has amassed a devoted cult following.
Stomp is an English percussive performance troupe that uses everyday objects, such as brooms and garbage cans, in its pieces. It has toured extensively since it was founded in 1991.
A line from the traditional Christmas carol “The Little Drummer Boy.”
The founder of Frederick’s of Hollywood, Frederick Mellinger, brought back the bikini from France, which got a customer arrested on Venice Beach.
Minneapolis musician Prince was one of the seminal musical talents of the ‘80s; his albums 1999, Purple Rain, and Sign o’ the Times were phenomenally successful.
A line from “Truckin’,” a 1970 blues-rock song by the Grateful Dead.
Cotton swabs were invented in the ‘20s by Leo Gerstenzang, who called them “Baby Gays.” The product was bought and (thankfully) rebranded “Q-Tips,” with the “Q” standing for “quality.”
“Feliz Navidad” is a Spanish-language Christmas song written by José Feliciano in 1970, a popular Christmas classic among English and Spanish speakers alike.
According to Dan Castellaneta, who voices Homer Simpson on The Simpsons, he borrowed Homer’s catchphrase from Laurel & Hardy comedian James Finlayson.
Masterpiece Theatre (now simply Masterpiece) is an anthology series on PBS that screens imported British comedy and drama; past shows include I, Claudius and Downton Abbey.
Reminiscent of the ads for bankruptcy attorneys that ran nonstop on TV during the ‘80s, in which a narrator would ask in a soothing, concerned baritone, “Divorced? Harassed by creditors?”
